# jam-actions-v0 Slice 23.5 — Reproducibility Cleanup (dataset-package LF pin).
#
# Pins line endings to LF on disk on every platform for the dataset package's
# text content AND for SHA-256 checksum manifests anywhere in the tree,
# regardless of git's core.autocrlf setting. Without these rules, Windows
# clones with autocrlf=true convert text files to CRLF on checkout; the
# packager writes content with LF (matching how the SHA-256 hashes were
# computed) so the on-disk bytes drift from the hashed content and the
# verifier reports hash mismatches across the entire package.
#
# Scope rationale (Slice 23.5):
#   - `*.sha256` covers the checksum manifest file class everywhere (catches
#     the parse-time bug originally found by the Slice 23 audit).
#   - `datasets/jam-actions-v0-public/**` covers all dataset-package text
#     files (catches the hash-mismatch problem when the package is verified
#     on a Windows fresh-clone). The package files are release artifacts
#     whose checksums are computed against canonical LF content; on-disk
#     LF is required for verification to pass.
#   - Other repo files (source, tests, top-level docs) keep their default
#     autocrlf behavior — narrow blast radius outside the dataset package.
#   - The CRLF-tolerant verifier in scripts/verify-public-package-checksums.ts
#     is defense in depth for the parse layer (file contents stripping
#     trailing \r on read); the LF pin here defends the byte-equality layer.
#
# Earned by Slice 23 audit (Gap #1, #13 — Windows-only reproducibility blocker).
*.sha256 text eol=lf
datasets/jam-actions-v0-public/** text eol=lf
